National</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>8EF4B681-D18C-435E-88B3-76A4D2FA2B2A</gtr:id><gtr:impact>Interview/ article for daily mail; Can watching a scary movie be good for your health. Discussion on how acute psychological stressors can alter immune function.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Media (as a channel to the public)</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:url>http://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-3868360/Can-watching-scary-movie-GOOD-health-Experts-reveal-scared-immune-boost-help-lose-weight.html</gtr:url><gtr:year>2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>UCLH research open day</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Regional</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>74E978A7-AFCB-4B7B-9E1B-BE680850EFF1</gtr:id><gtr:impact>A special exhibition of research and innovation at University College Hospital accommodating 50 interactive stalls where researchers demonstrate the latest technology and techniques tackling conditions such as cancer, dementia and arthritis.

