We had a great response from local community groups which we had never had contact with before.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Participants in your research and patient groups</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2014</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:disseminationOutput><gtr:description>Bi-yearly open day; Engaging Older Adults in Research</gtr:description><gtr:form>Participation in an activity, workshop or similar</gtr:form><gtr:geographicReach>Local</gtr:geographicReach><gtr:id>41CBD6CE-67A5-49F6-98A2-14EA97E6A7C6</gtr:id><gtr:impact>The research groups of Prof. Arne Akbar and Prof. Derek Gilroy from University College London have hosted a series of public engagement event aimed specifically at older adults. The events aimed to contact and engage with older adults from within the local community and UCL. Specifically we aimed to inform past, present and potential volunteers of the important research that has and is taking place on aging immunity within the Divisions of Infection and Immunity, and Medicine at UCL. We hoped to make our research understandable and accessible to all.</gtr:impact><gtr:partOfOfficialScheme>false</gtr:partOfOfficialScheme><gtr:primaryAudience>Public/other audiences</gtr:primaryAudience><gtr:year>2014,2015,2016</gtr:year></gtr:disseminationOutput></gtr:disseminationOutputs><gtr:exploitationOutputs/><gtr:furtherFundingOutputs/><gtr:impactSummaryOutputs/><gtr:intellectualPropertyOutputs/><gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:description>1) Multi-functional T cells have an intermediate telomere length in both young and old adults and are not restricted by excessive telomere length.

2) We have developed a multi-parameter flow cytometric method that enables the analysis of immune cell phenotype, functional capacity and telomere length in individual leucocytes. 

3) Acute stressors temporally change the composition of T cells in the peripheral blood and also have a lasting effect on T cell functions including cytotoxicity (capacity to kill), cytokine production (capacity to communicate with surrounding cells and tissue) and cell adhesion (capacity to migrate to inflamed areas). T cells are important regulators of immune responses and are involved in the clearance of infected and cancerous cells. These findings have furthered our understanding on how stressful events which induced stress hormone release (adrenaline release) may alter T cell immune function and thus the immune response. Further, although older individuals tend to have more stress responsive T cell, the responses of T cells to stress and ?AR-agonist (adrenaline) were the same in young (&amp;lt;40 years old) and old (65+) adults.

4) One focus of this project was to determine whether T cells from older adult had reduced avidity (ability to recognise and bind to infected cells) and then to examine the involvement of senescence in the change in avidity. This involved technology that relied on using immune cells isolated from individuals who had a certain HLA (tissue type) and had previously been infected with two common viruses. Following a substantial screening process of approximately 300 individuals, we identified 56 (27 old, 23 young, 6 middle age) individuals with a combined total of 82 appropriate T cell responses for the technology. Samples from these individuals were used to examine and compare the avidity of T cells in young and old individuals, and the relationship of avidity to cell markers for differentiation, senescence, and exhaustion. We found no association between T cell avidity with age, cell differentiation, senescence or exhaustion.</gtr:description><gtr:exploitationPathways>We have developed a multi-parameter flow cytometric method that enables the analysis of surface phenotype, cytokine production and telomere length in individual leucocytes. Through standardization with QuantumTM Cy5TM MESF beads, the results from different laboratories using different flow cytometers can be compared directly. This method will facilitate the use of telomere attrition as a biomarker in longitudinal studies and clinical trials.

Furthering our understanding of stress and endocrine induced regulation of immune function may lead to simple and economical opportunities to improve current interventions. Potential examples include enhancing T cell yields for allogeneic adoptive transfer and designing vaccine administration to specific times of day to coordinate with circadian rhythms of endocrine factors which may influence immune responses to the vaccine.</gtr:exploitationPathways><gtr:id>6721F74F-D247-41DB-9D73-B6A398B39668</gtr:id><gtr:sectors><gtr:sector>Healthcare,Pharmaceuticals and Medical Biotechnology,Other</gtr:sector></gtr:sectors></gtr:keyFindingsOutput><gtr:otherResearchOutputs/><gtr:policyInfluenceOutputs/><gtr:productOutputs/><gtr:researchDatabaseAndModelOutputs/><gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:researchMaterialOutput><gtr:description>We have developed a multi-parameter flow cytometric method that enables the analysis of surface phenotype, cytokine production and telomere length in individual leucocytes. Through standardization with QuantumTM Cy5TM MESF beads, the results from different laboratories using different flow cytometers can be compared directly.</gtr:description><gtr:id>EC10A889-3598-4BB9-A15B-432AF9C9FC12</gtr:id><gtr:impact>This method will facilitate the use of telomere attrition as a biomarker in longitudinal studies and clinical trials.</gtr:impact><gtr:providedToOthers>true</gtr:providedToOthers><gtr:title>Multi-parameter flow-FISH and standard curve</gtr:title><gtr:type>Physiological assessment or outcome measure</gtr:type><gtr:yearFirstProvided>2014</gtr:yearFirstProvided></gtr:researchMaterialOutput></gtr:researchMaterialOutputs><gtr:softwareAndTechnicalProductOutputs/><gtr:spinOutOutputs/></gtr:output><gtr:publications><gtr:publication url="http://gtr.rcuk.ac.uk:80/publication/0767DED0-68C8-47AB-8D1F-91ECE8099E15"><gtr:id>0767DED0-68C8-47AB-8D1F-91ECE8099E15</gtr:id><gtr:title>Multifunctional cytomegalovirus (CMV)-specific CD8(+) T cells are not restricted by 